arn a new language. Many local libraries offer free language classes. You can also borrow language tapes from the library to take home.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Join or start a book club with friends and neighbours.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you like music, learn to play an instrument or join a local choir or music group. Post an ad at your local college or music school; music students may be willing to give you lessons for a relatively low fee.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you love to dance, check out local classes in your area. You will find everything from ballroom and salsa to hip-hop.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to concerts. Live music need not be expensive. There are many places that have free music events throughout the year.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Check out adult education classes. They offer everything from sewing to Greek philosophy!</li>\r\n	<li>Get out in the garden more. Many communities now have allotments where people can grow their own vegetables.</li>\r\n	<li>Join a local amateur dramatic society. This is great fun, but learning lines is also good for your memory!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Activities that are good for brain health do not need to be expensive or boring.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Anything that stimulates you and that you enjoy is good for your brain!</p>\r\n\r\n<div style="display:none;">\r\n<div id="inlineCognitive" style="padding:10px; background:#fff;">\r\n<p>Cognitive function refers to memory, the ability to learn new information, process thoughts, speech and reading comprehension.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', '<h1>Cognitive Activity</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2 class="h-color">Room for improvement</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Your profile tells us that there is room to improve your social life and exercise your brain more.<br />\r\nWhile many of us know how to keep physically active, we may not think about keeping our brains active, or have time for it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Below you will find information about activities that can help you keep your brain healthy.<br />\r\nYou will also find your personalised plan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As we age, it is important to remain cognitively active to maintain our <a class="inlinePopup" href="#inlineCognitive">cognitive function</a>.<br />\r\nLearning new things and doing activities that challenge you is an excellent way to keep your brain healthy</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="images/riskfactors/cognitive/brain.png" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Activities that stimulate you mentally, physically and socially will keep your brain healthy and help prevent dementia.<br />\r\nFor a healthy brain, you need to look after your brain, body and heart. Brain health is especially important once you reach middle age. That is when changes start to occur.<br />\r\nResearch suggests that people who have few friends nearby and who spend a lot of time alone have a higher risk of dementia.<br />\r\nAlso people with little formal&nbsp; education and people in mid-life who do not exercise their brains much run a higher risk of developing dementia later in life.<br />\r\nCognitive function refers to memory, the ability to learn new information, process thoughts, speech and reading comprehension.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="images/riskfactors/cognitive/games.png" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>What can you do?</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Train your brain with crossword puzzles or online brain-training exercises.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Join your local library. This is a great alternative to buying books, and the staff can recommend interesting books on all sorts of topics.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Consider volunteering. This is a great way to meet new people while doing something that will benefit your community.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Learn a new language. Many local libraries offer free language classes. You can also borrow language tapes from the library to take home.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Join or start a book club with friends and neighbours.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you like music, learn to play an instrument or join a local choir or music group. Post an ad at your local college or music school; music students may be willing to give you lessons for a relatively low fee.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you love to dance, check out local classes in your area. You will find everything from ballroom and salsa to hip-hop.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Go to concerts. Live music need not be expensive. There are many places that have free music events throughout the year.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Check out adult education classes. They offer everything from sewing to Greek philosophy!</li>\r\n	<li>Get out in the garden more. Many communities now have allotments where people can grow their own vegetables.</li>\r\n	<li>Join a local amateur dramatic society. This is great fun, but learning lines is also good for your memory!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Activities that are good for brain health do not need to be expensive or boring.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Anything that stimulates you and that you enjoy is good for your brain!</p>\r\n\r\n<div style="display:none;">\r\n<div id="inlineCognitive" style="padding:10px; background:#fff;">\r\n<p>Cognitive function refers to memory, the ability to learn new information, process thoughts, speech and reading comprehension.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', '<h3>Further Supports</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Volunteer Scotland includes facility to search for volunteering opportunities in Scotland.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.volunteerscotland.net/">http://www.volunteerscotland.net/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>ALISS: access to local information to support self-management for people with long term health conditions. Includes search tool for health and wellbeing resources.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.aliss.org/">http://www.aliss.org/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Information from the National Health Service on conditions, treatments, local services and healthy living:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.nhs.uk/Pages/HomePage.aspx">http://www.nhs.uk/Pages/HomePage.aspx</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Glasgow learning, Includes search facility for evening and daytime classes In Glasgow:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.glasgowslearning.org.uk/learners/local_learning_provider_search">http://www.glasgowslearning.org.uk/learners/local_learning_provider_search</a></p>'),
	(9, 'en', 'Diet', 'images/libra/diet_amber.png', '<h1>Diet</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2 class="h-color">Keep this up!</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Your profile tells us that your current diet is healthy. Keep this up!<br />\r\nBelow you will find information on the importance of a healthy diet to your brain health. You may find new ways of incorporating healthy foods into your everyday diet!</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>A healthy diet is good for our overall health but it is also good for our brain health</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Researchers have found that diet and physical activity have a positive effect on our brain health.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Our eating habits may also play an important role in protecting us against dementia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="images/riskfactors/diet/pyramid.png" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>The Mediterranean Diet is thought to protect against dementia.</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The Mediterranean Diet has lots of fish, vegetables, pulses (beans, also known as legumes), fruit, cereals and olive oil, and only small amounts of dairy, meat and butter or margarine.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To eat a healthy and balanced diet, you need to combine several different types of foods - from each of the main food groups - in the right amounts. That way your body gets all the nutrients it needs while you maintain a healthy weight.&nbsp; This means you should eat:</li>\r\n	<li>Whole-grain breads, pasta and rice if available</li>\r\n	<li>Plenty of fruit and vegetables</li>\r\n	<li>Some milk, cheese and yoghurt</li>\r\n	<li>Some meat, fish, eggs, beans and other non-dairy sources of protein, and</li>\r\n	<li>Just a small amount of foods and drinks high in fat and/or sugar</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Eat more vegetables and fruit. </strong>Eat fruit and vegetables at every meal and for snacks as well. Carrots, celery, bananas and apples are easy to have on hand and make satisfying snacks. Fruit salads are a great way to eat a wide variety of healthy fruit.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Switch to whole-grain bread. </strong>Whole grains contain very few unhealthy fats. Try using whole-grain rice and pasta. Replace sugary breakfast cereals with porridge and add in blueberries or other fruit. If you need more sweetness, use honey instead of sugar.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Eat nuts. </strong>Try almonds, cashews, pistachios and walnuts. Try natural peanut butter. Nuts can be added to any meal but are also a great snack when you&rsquo;re out and about. Don&rsquo;t overdo it because nuts can be high in <a class="inlinePopup" href="#inlineCalorie">calories</a>. We recommend a handful of unsalted nuts 3 times per week. .</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Use olive oil </strong>as a healthy replacement for butter or margarine. Drizzle it on vegetables and bread. Make your own salad dressing by using a little olive oil, red wine or balsamic vinegar and crushed garlic. Add a squeeze of lemon juice if you wish. Olive oil, garlic, leeks and onions are a healthy alternative to shop-bought pasta sauces.<br />\r\n	<img alt="" src="images/riskfactors/diet/oil.png" /></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Eat fish </strong>at least twice a week. Salmon, trout and tuna are healthy choices. Grilling, baking or steaming fish is not only healthy but also takes very little time and effort. If you&rsquo;re on a budget, choose tinned sardines, tuna or mackerel. Eat it on whole-grain bread for a healthy lunch or evening snack.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Go low fat</strong>. Cut down on high-fat dairy products. Switch to skimmed milk, fat-free yogurt and low-fat cheese. Try frozen yogurt or natural yogurt as a healthy alternative to ice cream. Add in any fruit you wish for that extra sweetness!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2 class="h-color">What can I do?</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Watch the number of <a class="inlinePopup" href="#inlineCalorie">calories</a> you consume and maintain a healthy weight.</li>\r\n	<li>Limit the amount of fat in your diet. Use less animal fat like butter and margarine (known as saturated fats) and more vegetable fat like olive oil (known as unsaturated fats). Try to eliminate fast food, fried food and greasy snacks, which contain unhealthy trans-fatty acids.</li>\r\n	<li>Eat more fruits and vegetables, beans, whole grains and nuts.</li>\r\n	<li>Eat less sugar.</li>\r\n	<li>Fruit and vegetables are important parts of a healthy diet. Eating enough fruit and vegetables every day helps you avoid serious diseases, such as cardiovascular diseases and certain cancers.<br />\r\n	<img alt="" src="images/riskfactors/diet/vegies.png" /></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>Healthy Options</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Eat more fish every week. Have oily fish such as salmon, mackerel or sardines twice a week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Switch to olive oil. Instead of frying your food, choose grilling, baking or steaming.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use whole-grain pasta or rice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Add pulses (or legumes) to your everyday diet, for example peas, kidney beans or lentils.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Snack on fruit, nuts or vegetables.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Try not to skip meals, as you are more likely to eat larger portions when you do eat.<br />\r\nCut out/down on coffee/tea and sugary drinks and drink more water.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If your BMI is above the recommended limits for a healthy weight (over 25), you should reduce your <a class="inlinePopup" href="#inlineCalorie">calorie</a> intake. You can do this by following the advice above. Remember to limit your portion size as well, and not to exceed the recommended number of <a class="inlinePopup" href="#inlineCalorie">calories</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>BMI is a formula used to check whether a person is underweight, overweight or at a healthy weight. The formula divides your weight by the square of your height to get a BMI score. Anyone with a BMI score of between 18.5 to 25 is considered healthy, while 25 to 30 is overweight. A score of more than 30 is described as obese. <a href="http://www.nhs.uk/Tools/Pages/Healthyweightcalculator.aspx">Click here to calculate your BMI</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<div style="display:none;">\r\n<div id="inlineCalorie" style="padding:10px; background:#fff;">\r\n<p>A calorie is a unit of energy. It describes how much energy your body gets from eating or drinking. Most food and drinks contain calories. If you eat or drink more calories than you need, the leftover calories are converted to fat. If you only eat and drink the recommended number of daily calories, you will stay within a healthy weight range. Being active is also important because physical activity burns calories.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', '<h1>Diet</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2 class="h-color">Room for improvement</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Your profile tells us that your current diet could be improved.<br />\r\nMaking some small changes to your diet will help you maintain your brain health.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Below you will find information to help you make healthy eating part of your everyday routine.<br />\r\nYou will also find your personalised plan. This gives you a number of goals to choose from to help you develop healthy eating habits!</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>A healthy diet is good for our overall health but it is also good for our brain health</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Researchers have found that diet and physical activity have a positive effect on our brain health.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Our eating habits may also play an important role in protecting us against dementia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="images/riskfactors/diet/pyramid.png" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>The Mediterranean Diet is thought to protect against dementia.</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The Mediterranean Diet has lots of fish, vegetables, pulses (beans, also known as legumes), fruit, cereals and olive oil, and only small amounts of dairy, meat and butter or margarine.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>To eat a healthy and balanced diet, you need to combine several different types of foods - from each of the main food groups - in the right amounts. That way your body gets all the nutrients it needs while you maintain a healthy weight.&nbsp; This means you should eat:</li>\r\n	<li>Whole-grain breads, pasta and rice if available</li>\r\n	<li>Plenty of fruit and vegetables</li>\r\n	<li>Some milk, cheese and yoghurt</li>\r\n	<li>Some meat, fish, eggs, beans and other non-dairy sources of protein, and</li>\r\n	<li>Just a small amount of foods and drinks high in fat and/or sugar</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Eat more vegetables and fruit. </strong>Eat fruit and vegetables at every meal and for snacks as well. Carrots, celery, bananas and apples are easy to have on hand and make satisfying snacks. Fruit salads are a great way to eat a wide variety of healthy fruit.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Switch to whole-grain bread. </strong>Whole grains contain very few unhealthy fats. Try using whole-grain rice and pasta. Replace sugary breakfast cereals with porridge and add in blueberries or other fruit. If you need more sweetness, use honey instead of sugar.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Eat nuts. </strong>Try almonds, cashews, pistachios and walnuts. Try natural peanut butter. Nuts can be added to any meal but are also a great snack when you&rsquo;re out and about. Don&rsquo;t overdo it because nuts can be high in <a class="inlinePopup" href="#inlineCalorie">calories</a>. We recommend a handful of unsalted nuts 3 times per week. .</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Use olive oil </strong>as a healthy replacement for butter or margarine. Drizzle it on vegetables and bread. Make your own salad dressing by using a little olive oil, red wine or balsamic vinegar and crushed garlic. Add a squeeze of lemon juice if you wish. Olive oil, garlic, leeks and onions are a healthy alternative to shop-bought pasta sauces.<br />\r\n	<img alt="" src="images/riskfactors/diet/oil.png" /></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Eat fish </strong>at least twice a week. Salmon, trout and tuna are healthy choices. Grilling, baking or steaming fish is not only healthy but also takes very little time and effort. If you&rsquo;re on a budget, choose tinned sardines, tuna or mackerel. Eat it on whole-grain bread for a healthy lunch or evening snack.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Go low fat</strong>. Cut down on high-fat dairy products. Switch to skimmed milk, fat-free yogurt and low-fat cheese. Try frozen yogurt or natural yogurt as a healthy alternative to ice cream. Add in any fruit you wish for that extra sweetness!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2 class="h-color">What can I do?</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Watch the number of <a class="inlinePopup" href="#inlineCalorie">calories</a> you consume and maintain a healthy weight.</li>\r\n	<li>Limit the amount of fat in your diet. Use less animal fat like butter and margarine (known as saturated fats) and more vegetable fat like olive oil (known as unsaturated fats). Try to eliminate fast food, fried food and greasy snacks, which contain unhealthy trans-fatty acids.</li>\r\n	<li>Eat more fruits and vegetables, beans, whole grains and nuts.</li>\r\n	<li>Eat less sugar.</li>\r\n	<li>Fruit and vegetables are important parts of a healthy diet. Eating enough fruit and vegetables every day helps you avoid serious diseases, such as cardiovascular diseases and certain cancers.<br />\r\n	<img alt="" src="images/riskfactors/diet/vegies.png" /></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>Healthy Options</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Eat more fish every week. Have oily fish such as salmon, mackerel or sardines twice a week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Switch to olive oil. Instead of frying your food, choose grilling, baking or steaming.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use whole-grain pasta or rice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Add pulses (or legumes) to your everyday diet, for example peas, kidney beans or lentils.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Snack on fruit, nuts or vegetables.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Try not to skip meals, as you are more likely to eat larger portions when you do eat.<br />\r\nCut out/down on coffee/tea and sugary drinks and drink more water.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If your BMI is above the recommended limits for a healthy weight (over 25), you should reduce your <a class="inlinePopup" href="#inlineCalorie">calorie</a> intake. You can do this by following the advice above. Remember to limit your portion size as well, and not to exceed the recommended number of <a class="inlinePopup" href="#inlineCalorie">calories</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>BMI is a formula used to check whether a person is underweight, overweight or at a healthy weight. The formula divides your weight by the square of your height to get a BMI score. Anyone with a BMI score of between 18.5 to 25 is considered healthy, while 25 to 30 is overweight. A score of more than 30 is described as obese. <a href="http://www.nhs.uk/Tools/Pages/Healthyweightcalculator.aspx">Click here to calculate your BMI</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<div style="display:none;">\r\n<div id="inlineCalorie" style="padding:10px; background:#fff;">\r\n<p>A calorie is a unit of energy. It describes how much energy your body gets from eating or drinking. Most food and drinks contain calories. If you eat or drink more calories than you need, the leftover calories are converted to fat. If you only eat and drink the recommended number of daily calories, you will stay within a healthy weight range. Being active is also important because physical activity burns calories.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', '<h3>Further Supports</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.dohc.ie/publications/pdf/YourGuide_HealthyEating_FoodPyramid.pdf?direct=1">http://</a><a href="http://www.dohc.ie/publications/pdf/YourGuide_HealthyEating_FoodPyramid.pdf?direct=1">www.dohc.ie/publications/pdf/YourGuide_HealthyEating_FoodPyramid.pdf?direct=1</a></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Information on healthy diets and ideas and plans for healthy cooking</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.safefood.eu/">www.safefood.eu</a></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Facts and information on safe foods, healthy diets recipes and tips on eating well and weight loss</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(9, 'fr', 'Rgime', 'images/libra/diet_amber.png', '<h1>R&eacute;gime</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2 class="h-color">Continuez comme &ccedil;a&nbsp;! &nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Votre profil nous informe que votre r&eacute;gime alimentaire actuel est sain. Continuez ainsi&nbsp;!<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nVous trouverez ci-dessous des informations sur l&rsquo;importance d&rsquo;un r&eacute;gime alimentaire &eacute;quilibr&eacute; pour la sant&eacute; de votre cerveau et vous pourriez trouver de nouvelles mani&egrave;res d&rsquo;incorporer des aliments sains &agrave; votre r&eacute;gime quotidien&nbsp;!</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Une alimentation &eacute;quilibr&eacute;e est b&eacute;n&eacute;fique pour notre sant&eacute; mais &eacute;galement pour celle de notre cerveau</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Des chercheurs ont d&eacute;couvert que l&rsquo;alimentation et l&rsquo;activit&eacute; physique ont des effets positifs sur la sant&eacute; de notre cerveau.<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nNos habitudes alimentaires sont &eacute;galement susceptibles de jouer un r&ocirc;le non &nbsp;n&eacute;gligeable dans la protection contre la d&eacute;mence.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="images/riskfactors/diet/pyramid.png" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>On s&rsquo;accorde &agrave; dire que le r&eacute;gime m&eacute;diterran&eacute;en prot&egrave;ge contre la d&eacute;mence.</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Ce r&eacute;gime comporte beaucoup de poisson, de l&eacute;gumes secs (que l&rsquo;on appelle &eacute;galement l&eacute;gumineuses) ou normaux, de fruits, de c&eacute;r&eacute;ales, d&rsquo;huile d&rsquo;olive, tout en incluant de petites quantit&eacute;s de produits laitiers, de viande et de beurre ou de margarine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Afin d&rsquo;adopter des habitudes alimentaires saines et &eacute;quilibr&eacute;es, il vous faudra combiner diff&eacute;rentes sortes de nourritures, provenant de tous les groupes alimentaires, et ce en quantit&eacute; appropri&eacute;e. De cette fa&ccedil;on, votre corps obtiendra toutes les substances nutritives dont il a besoin et votre poids demeurera raisonnable. Dans cette optique, voici ce qu&rsquo;il vous faudrait manger :</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Du pain complet, des p&acirc;tes et du riz si disponible</li>\r\n	<li>Beaucoup de fruits et l&eacute;gumes</li>\r\n	<li>Un peu de lait, de fromage et de yaourt</li>\r\n	<li>Un peu de viande, de poisson, d&rsquo;&oelig;ufs, de l&eacute;gumes et autres sources de prot&eacute;ines non laiti&egrave;res, ainsi que</li>\r\n	<li>De petites quantit&eacute;s de nourritures et de boissons riches en graisses et/ou en sucres.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Il vous faudra manger <strong>plus de fruits et de l&eacute;gumes</strong>, &agrave; chaque repas et pour grignoter &eacute;galement. Les carottes, le c&eacute;leri, les bananes et les pommes sont facile &agrave; transporter et constituent des en-cas substantiels. Les salades de fruit sont un bon moyen de consommer une grande vari&eacute;t&eacute; de fruits sains.</li>\r\n	<li>Choisissez du <strong>pain complet</strong> plut&ocirc;t que du pain blanc. Le pain complet comporte tr&egrave;s peu de mauvaise mati&egrave;re grasse.</li>\r\n	<li>Essayez aussi le<strong> riz complet</strong> et les <strong>p&acirc;tes compl&egrave;tes</strong>. Remplacez les c&eacute;r&eacute;ales riches en sucre du petit-d&eacute;jeuner par du porridge et ajoutez-y quelques myrtilles ou d&rsquo;autres fruits. Si vous d&eacute;sirez quelque chose de plus sucr&eacute;, utilisez du miel &agrave; la place du sucre.</li>\r\n	<li>Mangez des<strong> fruits &agrave; coques</strong>. Essayez les amandes, les noix de cajou, les pistaches et les noix. Essayez &eacute;galement le beurre de cacahu&egrave;tes nature. Les fruits &agrave; coques peuvent &ecirc;tre incorpor&eacute;s &agrave; tous les repas mais ils font &eacute;galement de bons en-cas lorsque vous voyagez. Pas d&rsquo;exc&egrave;s cependant, car les fruits &agrave; coques sont souvent riches en calories ; nous recommandons d&rsquo;en manger une poign&eacute;e sans sel ajout&eacute; trois fois par semaine.</li>\r\n	<li>Utilisez de l&rsquo;<strong>huile d&rsquo;olive</strong>, meilleure pour la sant&eacute; que le beurre ou la margarine. D&eacute;posez-en quelques gouttes sur les l&eacute;gumes et le pain. Composez votre propre sauce pour la salade en utilisant un peu d&rsquo;huile d&rsquo;olive, du vin rouge ou du vinaigre balsamique et de l&rsquo;ail pil&eacute;. Ajoutez-y un soup&ccedil;on de jus de citron si vous le d&eacute;sirez. L&rsquo;huile d&rsquo;olive,<br />\r\n	l&rsquo;ail, les poireaux et les oignons sont des substituts bien plus sains que les sauces que vous pourrez acheter en boutique.</li>\r\n	<li>Mangez du<strong> poisson </strong>au moins deux fois par semaine. Le saumon, la truite et le thon sont d&rsquo;excellents choix pour votre organisme. Griller, paner ou faire cuire votre poisson &agrave; la vapeur n&rsquo;est pas seulement sain, mais cela demande &eacute;galement tr&egrave;s peu de temps et d&rsquo;&eacute;nergie. Si vous avez peu de moyens, optez pour des sardines en bo&icirc;te, du thon ou encore du maquereau en conserve. Les consommer sur du pain complet au d&eacute;jeuner, voire comme en-cas du soir, vous offre un repas sain.</li>\r\n	<li>Adoptez un<strong> r&eacute;gime faible en graisses</strong>. Diminuez votre consommation de produits laitiers caloriques. Choisissez du lait &eacute;cr&eacute;m&eacute; plut&ocirc;t qu&rsquo;entier, ainsi que du yaourt et du fromage &agrave; z&eacute;ro pourcent.<br />\r\n	Essayez le yaourt glac&eacute; ou nature, car c&rsquo;est une alternative saine &agrave; la cr&egrave;me glac&eacute;e. Afin de rendre l&rsquo;ensemble plus doux, pourquoi ne pas y ajouter quelques fruits de votre choix ?<br />\r\n	&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2 class="h-color">Que dois-je faire ?</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Surveillez le nombre de calories que vous consommez et maintenez-vous &agrave; un poids raisonnable.</li>\r\n	<li>Limitez la quantit&eacute; de graisses au sein de votre alimentation. Utilisez moins de graisses animales telles que le beurre et la margarine (aussi appel&eacute;es graisses satur&eacute;es) et plus de graisses v&eacute;g&eacute;tales telles que l&rsquo;huile d&rsquo;olive (graisses insatur&eacute;es). Essayez autant que<br />\r\n	possible de bannir de votre alimentation la restauration rapide, la friture et les en-cas gras, qui contiennent des acides gras trans, lesquels sont mauvais pour la sant&eacute;.</li>\r\n	<li>Consommez plus de fruits et de l&eacute;gumes, de l&eacute;gumes secs, d&rsquo;aliments complets et de fruits secs.</li>\r\n	<li>Consommez moins de sucre.</li>\r\n	<li>Les fruits et les l&eacute;gumes jouent un r&ocirc;le important au sein d&rsquo;une alimentation &eacute;quilibr&eacute;e En consommant suffisamment de fruits et de l&eacute;gumes au quotidien, vous pourrez &eacute;viter des maladies graves de type cardiovasculaires ainsi que certains cancers.<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	<img alt="" src="images/riskfactors/diet/vegies.png" /></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>Les alternatives sant&eacute;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Mangez plus de poisson chaque semaine. Consommez-en deux fois par semaine (saumon, maquereau ou sardines) avec de l&rsquo;huile.<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nPrenez de l&rsquo;huile d&rsquo;olive &agrave; la place du beurre. Plut&ocirc;t que de faire frire votre nourriture, faites-la griller, pr&eacute;parez-la au four ou &agrave; la vapeur.<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nOptez pour les p&acirc;tes et le riz complets.<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nAjoutez des l&eacute;gumes secs (ou l&eacute;gumineuses) &agrave; votre alimentation quotidienne : pensez aux haricots rouges ou verts ainsi qu&rsquo;aux lentilles.<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nEn guise d&rsquo;en-cas, prenez des fruits, des fruits &agrave; coque ou bien des l&eacute;gumes.<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n<strong>Essayez autant que possible de ne pas sauter les repas, car dans ce cas vous &ecirc;tes susceptible de manger de plus grandes portions pour vous rattraper. Il vous faudra diminuer autant que faire se peut votre consommation de caf&eacute;, de th&eacute; et de boissons sucr&eacute;es pour privil&eacute;gier l&rsquo;eau.</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nSi votre Indice de Masse Corporelle d&eacute;passe la limite recommand&eacute;e (c&rsquo;est-&agrave;-dire au-dessus de 25), vous devrez diminuer votre apport en calories ; cela est possible si vous suivez les conseils dispens&eacute;s ci-dessus. N&rsquo;oubliez pas de limiter &eacute;galement la taille de vos portions alimentaires, afin de ne pas d&eacute;passer l&rsquo;apport en calories recommand&eacute;.<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nL&rsquo;IMC est une formule que l&rsquo;on utilise pour v&eacute;rifier si une personne est trop maigre, en surpoids ou si son poids est dans les normes. Cette formule divise votre poids par le carr&eacute; de votre taille afin d&rsquo;obtenir une estimation de votre indice. Une personne poss&eacute;dant un indice entre 18,5 et 25 est consid&eacute;r&eacute;e comme en bonne sant&eacute; ; de 25 &agrave; 30,<br />\r\nla personne est en surpoids. Une estimation sup&eacute;rieure &agrave; 30 correspond &agrave; une personne ob&egrave;se. Cliquez ici pour calculer votre IMC.</p>', '<h1>R&eacute;gime</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2 class="h-color">Une am&eacute;lioration est possible<br />\r\n&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Votre profil nous informe que vous pourriez am&eacute;liorer votre r&eacute;gime. Apporter quelques petites modifications &agrave; celui-ci vous permettrait de maintenir votre cerveau en bonne sant&eacute;.<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nVous trouverez ci-dessous des informations qui vous aideront &agrave; inclure des repas &eacute;quilibr&eacute;s au sein de vos habitudes quotidiennes. Vous y trouverez &eacute;galement votre programme personnalis&eacute;. Celui-ci vous propose un certain nombre d&rsquo;objectifs que vous<br />\r\npourrez choisir en vue de d&eacute;velopper des habitudes alimentaires saines !<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\